version: 1
display_name: VCFI-9X-000073 - The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations PostgreSQL service must use Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) for log timestamps.
global_description: |-
  If time stamps are not consistently applied and there is no common time reference, it is difficult to perform forensic analysis.

  Time stamps generated by PostgreSQL must include date and time. Time is commonly expressed in UTC, a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFI-9X-000073
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000374-DB-000322
  cci:
    - CCI-001890
  nist:
    - AU-8 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_operations_postgresql:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations PostgreSQL service must use Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) for log timestamps.
    control_id: VCFI-9X-000073
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      As a database administrator, perform the following at the command prompt:

      # su - postgres -c "/opt/vmware/vpostgres/current/bin/psql -p 5433 -A -t -c 'SHOW log_timezone;'"

      Example result:

      UTC

      If the "log_timezone" setting is not configured to "UTC", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      If time stamps are not consistently applied and there is no common time reference, it is difficult to perform forensic analysis.

      Time stamps generated by PostgreSQL must include date and time. Time is commonly expressed in UTC, a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC.
    remediation: |-
      As a database administrator, perform the following at the command prompt:

      # su - postgres -c "/opt/vmware/vpostgres/current/bin/psql -p 5433 -A -t -c \"ALTER SYSTEM SET log_timezone TO 'UTC';\""

      Reload the PostgreSQL service by running the following command:

      # systemctl restart vpostgres-repl.service
